state.label: in these species the tip of the posterior process contacts or nearly contact the frontals
there is no contact between the mesethmoid and frontal bones in loricariids, astroblepids, trichomycterids, and Scoloplax dolicholophi
in contrast, the mesethmoid of S. dolicholophia (Fig. 5) and all other loricarioids lacks a slender anterior process
in Scoloplax dicra, S. distolothrix, and S. empousa the mesethmoid bears a slender midline anterior process
present and robust in Nematogenys, trichomycterids, and most other siluroid
mesethmoid lateral cornua are greatly reduced or absent in astroblepids, callichthyids, loricariids, and scoloplacids
the antorbital process is directed laterally in Scoloplax dicra, S. distolothrix, and S. empousa
all other loricarioids; directed posteriorly in S. dolocholophia
open in most siluroid
in astroblepids, loricariids, and scoloplacids there are no open cranial fontanelle
all other scoloplacids maintain the contact between the hyomandibula and frontal, but the latter bone in these species does not bear an articular process
in Scoloplax distolothrix and S. empousa the anterior process of the hyomandibula contacts a pair of discrete, slender processes on the lateral face of the frontal bone

partial to nearly complete occlusion is found intrichomycterids, which share a separate supracleithrum with Nematogenys (see character 11 below), and in callichthyids (Fig. 7B), astroblepids, and loricariids, all of which have the supracleithrum fused with the pterotic
in scoloplacids the swimbladder fenestra is large and not occluded by the compound pterotic
in Scoloplax dicra and other oricarioids the anterior margin of the basioccipital is straight
in S. distolothrix and S. dolicholophia the basioccipital processes are short spikes
in S. empousa the basioccipital has a complex laminar ossification projecting anteriorly for about one-half the length of the prootic
in S. distolothrix and S. empousa the transverse shelf is discontinuous as in other loricarioids
in Scoloplax dicra and S. dolicholophia the transverse shelf is continuous across the posteroventral margin of the basioccipital
in constrast to the condition in all other loricarioids where the exoccipitals are distinct
in scoloplacids there are no separate exoccipital bones
among loricarioids this condition is present in Nematogenys and trichomycterids
in callichthyids, astroblepids, loricariids, and scoloplacids these elements are fused into a compound ossification (Baskin 1973;Howes 1983b), hereafter referred to as the compound pterotic
in other loricarioids the process is blunt and rounded
in Scoloplax dolicholophia the anterior pterotic process is sharply pointed

in most siluroids and in nematogenyids and trichomycterids the dorsal process of the cleithrum projects dorsally through an aperture in the cranium between the pterotic, supracleithrum, and epiotic which is completely open dorsally
in loricariids and scoloplacids the dorsal process of the cleithrum projects into a shallow facet in the compound pterotic-supracleithrum; there is no aperture
in all other loricarioids the pterotic process is not similarly elongate, not reaching beyond the supraoccipital spine tip
in Scoloplax dolicholophia the posterior pterotic process is elongate, reaching posteriorly beyond the tip of the supraoccipital spine
in Scoloplax dicra and S. dolicholophia the anterior portion of the parasphenoid extends to the lateral ethmoid posterior margin as in other loricarioids
in S. distolothrix and S. empousa the parasphenooid extends anteriorly to the anterior margin of the lateral ethmoids
a vomer is present and separate in all other loricarioids
scoloplacids lack a separate vomer
in Scoloplax dicra the lateral cephalic canal enters the sphenotic from the pterotic as in other loricarioids
in all other scoloplacids the lateral cephalic canal is reduced and does not enter the sphenotic
in S. dolicholophia the lateral cephalic canal is absent
a preopercular canal is present in Scoloplaxdicra
all other scoloplacids lack a preopercular canal
most siluroids share the presence of four or five foramina
all other loricarioids have three or fewer preopercle foramina
in Diplomystes, Nematogenys, and most siluroids the preopercular canal enters the dentary bone
in all other loricarioids the canal does not enter the dentary
in Nematogenys, trichomycterids and most siluroids the lacrimal/antorbital bears a portion of the anterior infraorbital canal
in all other loricarioids, the lachrimal-antorbital, when present, does not bear a canal
in most siluroids the premaxillae are firmly associated with the mesethmoid lateral cornua via ankylosis or ligaments
in all other loricarioids the premaxillae are not closely or firmly attached to the mesethmoid and the upper jaws are highly mobile
these processes are absent or not expanded in all other loricarioids
in Astroblepids the premaxillae bear expanded dorsolateral and anterolateral processes
among loricarioids this morphology is present in Nematogenys, trichomycterids and callichthyids
in scoloplacids, astroblepids, and loricariids tooth cusps are bifid; symmetrically bifid in scoloplacids and astroblepids
asymmetrically bifid in loricariid
in all other scoloplacids the palatine is straight, its lateral surface flat
the bone is cup shaped lateral to the dorsal shaft
in Scoloplax dicra, S. distolothrix, S. empousa and other loricarioids the metapterygoid is relatively large, its dorsal ramus contacting the palatine
the posterior ramus is greatly reduced and the small dorsal ramus does not contact the palatine
in Scoloplax dicra the posterior ramus of the metapterygoid makes a long synchondral joint with the dorsal magin of the quadrate
in all other scoloplacids the extent of the joint is relatively short, much less than one-half the length of the quadrate dorsal margin
in nematogenyids, trichomycterids, callichthyids (except some Corydoras) and scoloplacids contact of the metapterygoid with the hyomandibula is synchondral
astroblepids and loricariids share a sutural contact between these bones
in most catfishes the coronoid process of the dentary projects dorsally, as do the dentary teeth
relative to the remainder of the suspensorium, the mandibles are rotated ventromedially such that the coronoid process projects laterally, while the lower jaw teeth project anterior

in siluroids the truncus hyomandibularis branch of the facial nerve enters the hyomandibula on its medial surface and exits the bone on either the lateral surface or the ventral margin of the hyomandibula
in all other scoloplacids the nerve exits the bone on the lateral surface
present in all other loricarioids and most siluroids
the interopercle is absent in scoloplacids and loricariids
this process is absent in all other loricarioid
the anterohyal of Scoloplax empousa bears a small process on the posterior margin which articulates with the first branchiostegal
most siluroids have five or more branchiostegal rays
all other loricarioids have four or fewer branchiostegal rays
in loricarioids, like most siluroids, the hypohyal bears a large foramen through which project an anterior process of the urohyal
the hypohyal foramen is absent in S. distolothrix and S. dolicholophia; the urohyal processes are similarly reduced
in S. empousa the hypohyal foramen is reduced, as is the urohyal anterior process, which does not project into the hypohyal foramen
anterior processes are present in Scoloplax dicra
are absent in S. distolothrix and S. dolicholophia
these processes are reduced to small rounded projections in S. empousa
Scoloplax dicra has 27 total vertebrae
Scoloplax distolothrix and S. empousa share 26 total vertebrae
whereas S. dolicholophia has 25
in scoloplacids and most siluroids the first post-Weberian centrum articulates with the Weberian complex synchondrally, via a ligamentous peg and socket articulation
in astroblepids and loricariids the articulation is either a direct ankylosis (Astroblepus, some loricariids) or via a strong interdigitating suture
in Nematogenys, trichomycterids, and callichthyids the rib articulates with a transverse parapophysis on the sixth centrum
in all other loricarioids the rib articulates with a concave socket on the ventrolateral portion of the centrum
ventral parapophyses are present in Nematogenys, trichomycterids, callichthyids, and scoloplacids (eleventh centrum only), and most siluroids
parapophyses are absent from the vertebrae in astroblepids and loricariids
in Nematogenys and trichomycterids (except glanapterygines; Pinna 1989:370, fig. 11) the dorsal hypurals (3-5) are separate
in other loricarioids the dorsal hypural elements are fused to the compound caudal centrum
in contrast to the non-expanded morphology in all other scoloplacids
in Scoloplax dolicholophia the distal tip of the transverse process is expanded
this element is absent or unossified in all other loricarioids
in scoloplacids astroblepids and loricariids a lateral bone is present be tween the second proximal radial transverse process and the rib of the sixth centrum
Scoloplax dicra, S. empousa, and S. dolicholophia share with outgroup loricarioids the presence of four or more segmented dorsal-fin rays and five proximal radials
Scoloplax distolothrix has three soft dorsal-fin rays and a total of four proximal radials
in all other loricarioids the transverse shelf, when present, is not expanded
in astroblepids and loricariids the transverse shelf of the first anal-fin proximal radial is greatly expanded
in Scoloplax dolicholophia the pectoral-spine posterior margin bears four or five large, recurved serrations

characteristic of the pectoral spines of Nematogenys and many siluroids. Among loricarioids, pectoral spine serrations are also found in callichthyids and some loricariids (Oxyropsis, Hypoptopoma), absent in trichomycterids, astroblepids and all other scoloplacid
Scoloplax dicra shares the presence of six segmented (soft) pectoral-fin rays with the majority of loricariid and astroblepid catfishes
Scoloplax distolothrix and S.empousa share the presence of five soft rays
S. dolicholophia has four
a secondary foramen is absent in Scoloplax dicra, S. dolicholophia and other loricarioids
in Scoloplax distolothrix and S. empousa the cleithrum bears a small foramen below the dorsal process on the posterior face
in Scoloplax dicra, S. distolothrix, S. empousa, and outgroup loricarioids the opening of the abductor chamber is medial
in S. dolicholophia the opening lies dorsal relative to the cleithrum vertical lamina
the dorsal surface is relatively flat. All other scoloplacids lack the ventral cavity
a large circular cavity occupies the ventral surface
a similar structure is not known elsewhere among siluroids
autapomorphic for scoloplacids among siluroids is the presence of a large, shield-shaped plate located in the skin above the dorsal surface of the lateral ethmoids and mesethmoid
Scoloplax dolicholophia and all other loricarioids lack a lateral plate
in Scoloplax dicra, S. distolothrix, and S. empousa there is a small bony plate bearing one to several odontodes at the lateral corner of the lateral ethmoid
in Diplomystes (Arratia 1987:25), Arius, Nematogenys, trichomycterids, callichthyids, and other catfishes the cranial attachment involves the vomer in addition to other cranial bones
in all other loricarioids the pterygoethmoid ligament is absent or does not involve the cranium
in scoloplacids the dorsal ramus of the metapterygoid is closely attached to the palatine via a short ligament
in trichomycterids, scoloplacids, astroblepids and loricariids there is a distinct ligament between the metapterygoid and the posterior portion of the palatine
absent in trichomycterids, Nematogenys, and numerous outgroup siluroids
callichthyids, scoloplacids, astroblepids, and loricariids share the derived presence of a ligament between the mesethmoid and the maxilla
although the premaxillae are highly mobile in scoloplacids, these catfishes lack the associated specialized ligament attachments just discussed
in callichthyids and astroblepids a single ligament is present between the mesethmoid and premaxilla
two separate ligaments are present in loricariids
absent in all other loricarioids
a ligament between the posterior portion of the palatine and the lateral ethmoid is present in astroblepids
all other loricarioids and siluroids have an interoperculo-mandibular ligament
scoloplacids, astroblepids and loricariids share the loss of the interoperculo-mandibular ligament
all other loricarioids lack the operculo-mandibular ligament

this new couple is a result of the presence of a ligament between the anteroventral margin of the opercle and a posterior process of the anguloarticular in loricariids, observed in Neoplecostomus, Hypostomus, Isorineloricaria, Cochliodon
this ligament is reduced or absent in all other loricarioids
astroblepids possess a thick, broad ligament between the opercle and the expanded interhyal bone
in Nematogenys and trichomycterids the adductor mandibulae is relatively undifferentiated and there is no separate retractor tentaculi
a separate retractor tentaculi is present in all other loricarioids
in most siluroids the retractor tentaculi originates from the posterior portion of the suspensorium either behind or just beneath the eye
in scoloplacids, astroblepids, and loricariids the retractor originates from the skull, anterior to the orbit
in most siluroids, Nematogenys, and trichomycterids the adductor mandibulae is little differentiated, no part of which inserts directly or indirectly on the premaxilla
anterodorsal fibers of the adductor approach the premaxillae, but make no direct insertion
in scoloplacids, astroblepids, and loricariids the fibers insert directly onto the premaxilla and are well differentiated from the cheek portion of the adductor
there is no homologous muscle present in any other loricarioid nor siluroid
in loricariids the adductor is further subdivided, with a medial division having an indirect tendinous insertion onto the premaxilla
in all other loricarioids the extensor tentaculi is not subdivided
in loricariids the extensor tentaculi muscle, a derivative of the adductor arcus palatini, is subdivided with two distinct insertions on the palatine
in most siluroids and all other loricarioids the geniohyoideus is not subdivided, its insertion entirely on the dentary
in astroblepids and loricariids the geniohyoideus is bilaterally subdivided
in all other loricarioids the hyohyoideus is not divided
in scoloplacids (Fig. 28, hhi), astroblepids and loricariids the hyohyoideus inferioris muscle is laterally divided
an oral disk is absent in all other loricarioids
in loricariids and astroblepids the fleshy lips are developed into broad, expanded flaps that are continuous at both the midline and laterally around the maxilla
in most siluroids the right and left halves of the lower jaws are tightly associated with one another via connective tissue at the midline
among loricarioids, this tight attachment is absent in astroblepids and loricariids and some but not all trichomycterids
the hyomandibular cartilage is absent in the mochokids Chiloglanis, Atopochilus, and all other loricarioids
in astroblepids and loricariids a large, spherical mass of cartilage and connective tissue is situated between the lower jaw symphysis and the hyoid arch
in most siluroids and loricarioids the nostrils are separated by a flap of skin equal or greater than the width of the posterior nostril
in astroblepids and loricariids the nostrils are juxtaposed, separated by at most a thin vertical skin fold
in Scoloplax dicra these barbels are uniramous, occuring as single elements
in Scoloplax distolothrix, S. empousa, and S. dolicholophia the mandibular barbels are biramous, occuring as double elements distinctly separate to near their bases
pelvic platelets are absent in all other scoloplacids
Scoloplax dicra has a pair of small bony platelets at the skin surface between the pelvic-fin base and anus
